Title: Human Animal
Comment:
Andy is the human animal. Forced to work a dull desk job, born to dance under the neon lights. 

The LCD meets Talking Heads inspiration for Total Giovanni of course makes me think of Andy. And the theme of the track is very on brand for him. 

I know Andy is a huge appreciator of many types of music. He has a primal animal in himself that needs to be expressed through movement / dance. I think this song nicely captures his duality of working at an ad company by day, and unleashing his musical animal by night.

Andy‚Äôs an angel. Hangry? He‚Äôs still nice though. Stressed at work? Andy‚Äôs giggling. All in, this is why I picked this song for him . Title: Circle of Life
Comment: You're walking home after another soul-sucking day in the office. The city isn't what you hoped. You've made no friends and have nothing to look forward to tonight but leftovers. You round the corner and it hits you: "NAAAANTS' INGONYAMA BAGITHI BABA!" You stop in your tracks. The busker is a beam of light. Something inside of you stirs. Surprising yourself, you chant: "Ingonyama nengw' enambala." First softly, then stronger. Passersby join in - the hotdog man, a bike courier. The sound swells! The busker catches your eye. You nod. Traffic still, you step into the street and sing: "From the day we arrive on the planet ..." The song flows from deep inside. Tears of joy stream down your face. You sing! You sing and the city sings with you! It ends as suddenly as it began. The street is as it was, people disperse. Your heart is pounding and you're a mess, but you feel utterly full. You try to thank the busker - but they're gone. You pause and take a breath. Then you walk on, whistling.

Title: Holding Out for a Hero - Single Version
Album: The Very Best of Bonnie Tyler
Comment:
"Where have all the good men gone and where are all the gods?
Where's the streetwise Hercules to fight the risin' odds?
Isn't there a white knight upon a fiery steed?
Late at night, I toss and I turn and I dream of what I need"

A red-pilled Bonnie Tyler incessantly negs you through your EarPods as you near the finish line.  You catch your reflection in a nearby building... you look more like a neckbearded incel than a streetwise Hercules.  But Bonnie is there at the end waiting for you, tossing and turning and dreaming of a white knight fulfilling her every need.  You push forward, every sinew straining to fulfill your promise.

You won't be an incel for long.
